<DOC><DOCNO> AP900227-0182 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-90 2122EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Schwartz     02-27 0240</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Schwartz,0247</SECOND><HEAD>Bataan Death March Prosecutor Dead at Age 80</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Benjamin F. Schwartz, a U.S. Navy attorneywho helped prosecute a Japanese general after World War II fororganizing the Bataan Death March, has died. He was 80.   Schwartz died Sunday of heart failure at his Los Angeles home,said his widow, Lois.   Schwartz was a Navy prosecutor at the Manila, Philippines, trialof Gen. Masaharu Homma, who was convicted of organizing the 1942death march on the Philippines' Bataan Peninsula. Homma wasexecuted.   American and Filipino soldiers defending Bataan and Corrgidor, arocky fortress in Manila Bay, were defeated by Japanese forces inApril and May of 1942. Under Homma, the Japanese forced anestimated 60,000 of the soldiers to march about 70 miles to prisoncamps. About 10,000 of the prisoners died of starvation and othermistreatment during the march.   Schwartz joined the antitrust division of the Justice Departmentbefore the war. He later joined the Navy's Industrial IncentiveDivision, speaking to defense plant workers to encourage increasedproductivity, before he became a Navy prosecutor.   After the Manila trial, Schwartz entered private law practice.He mounted an unsuccessful campaign for state Assembly in 1952 andlater became a member of the Democratic Party's state centralcommittee.   In addition to his widow, Schwartz is survived by four childrenand four grandchildren.   Services were scheduled for Wednesday at Mount Sinai MemorialPark in Los Angeles.</TEXT></DOC>